node.text:
1) start with the slower/controlled crossover steps
2) Gradually speed it up and cover more distance laterally as you become comfortable
3) Turn it into a freestyle with cross over/cross under steps
4) REP IT

Typically I’d spend 3-5 min on a drill like this towards the end of a warmup. 

📝 Ankle mobility in sports is far more than linear dorsi flexion. We need to create shin angles over pinky toe side and over big toe side. 

I’ve seen a lot players who pass standard dorsi flexion range tests who actually have poor ankle mobility in sports. 

The drill I’m doing here is far more than just ankle mobility and creating good shin angles in games requires a combination of foot/ankle/hip mobility and stability that all ties together with proper timing/skill in the movement. 

The athletes who are the best at creating optimal shin angles didn’t build it through 3x5 drills in the weightroom (this isn’t bad... it’s just a very small part of the process). They build it through fluid/coordinated movement. 

For advanced ball handlers you could train this same thing through zig zag dribbling drills. But for average ball handlers, the ball control becomes the limiting factor which leads to slow/upright movement and the body angles don’t get challenged like they would without the ball.

Give this one a try. Let’s build 🔋.

🎥 @thatcalvinmai 
🎥 @suns @dbook

node.text:
Here’s a SIMPLE drill you guys can do to build your lateral change of direction! In The Speed Code we have 2 key intro phases— 1) Healthy Human Foundations and 2) Freak Athlete Foundations. 

Healthy human phase is designed to get you moving optimally. Too many athletes are training specifically for their sport without developing optimal movement as a human first. This always leads to breakdowns in the body eventually. Building a base of movement quality, fitness and tissue tolerance can decrease our risk of injury long term. 

In phase 2, Our Freak Athlete Foundation phase aims to build the qualities needed for elite speed, agility and vertical jump. This is where we develop the physical/neuromuscular traits needed for high level athleticism and expose the body to more specific stresses in order to prepare the body for the rest of the program. 

I’m excited to get you guys going on the program. We’re almost ready for launch! @spellmanperformance and I are excited to create some monsters in ALL sports. Let’s build.

node.text:
This advice is actually 🔑 for players of all sizes, but especially undersized players. You can’t be small AND lack quickness. End to end speed doesn’t need to be great but the quickness has to be there to hang defensively at the highest levels. Yes, there’s many more things you need beyond quickness... but think of a requisite level of quickness as your key to get on the floor in the first place. 

Good news is we CAN significantly improve quickness. And it happens through a combination of body (actual physiological changes) and brain (perceptual abilities). If you’re improving your brain quickness (perception-action) we’re “slowing the game down”, which improves anticipation and reaction abilities. This comes from specific reaction training, film work, game experience, etc.

If you’re improving your body quickness you’re changing actual physiological traits (neuromuscular gains, musculotendon, etc) This always shows up in drills and testing situations but doesn’t automatically transfer to live play. 

We want to attack both brain and body quickness! But body quickness has diminishing returns, while brain quickness continues to improve across your entire career. I’ve had numerous NBA PG clients that I can still outperform on all quickness tests, but they’re quicker than me in games. Why? They anticipate better. They see more frames per second than me. They’ve guarded more high level moves than me, which makes their reaction speed far better. 

In our upcoming program the speed code we attack both brain and body quickness. Can’t wait to get you guys on the program!
🎥 Youtube/Tom Tankelewicz II
Youtube/Always Hoops
Youtube/Evin Gualberto
Youtube?NBA

node.text:
For the full 15 minute video check out TheEdgeU.com! Continuing our conversation w/ squats and approach jumps, in this video we discussed the importance of joint angle specificity. 

Deep squats “work” your muscles better. But they massively under train the joint angles that actually matter for the approach jump. The literature tells us that in beginners training in a deep range of motion and long muscle length leads to gains at multiple other joint angles and shorter muscle lengths... but in trained individuals we only see strength improvements at or near the joint angle being trained. So getting super strong in deep ranges won’t translate much to strength in partial ranges, especially considering that we only train these partial ranges at 70% max load when deep squatting. Now, deep squats and parallel do have advantages such as improved hypertrophy (which could be good or could be bad for approach jump). Also, deeper squats may be better for injury reduction. In this series we’re strictly looking at approach jumps to determine what exercises can actually increase “force potential”. In the next part of the series I’ll talk about why I don’t use quarter squats year round and give you some safer alternatives that may work even better than bilateral quarter squats! Stay tuned.
🎥 @thatcalvinmai 
🐰 @maxwellpearce @hamilt0njr

node.text:
Let’s discuss...

(For the full 15 minute video checkout TheEdgeU.com- link in bio). In the past we’ve discussed squats and jumping quite a bit on EdgeU and @strong_by_science and I have discussed it from a muscle standpoint, biomechanical stand point, individual joint torque standpoint and now from a force output point of view. Remember this particular discussion is ONLY looking at it from a force perspective... it gets more complicated than this!

From my research pulling from hundreds of elite athlete force plate tests and DSI testing, I believe heavy squats to parallel actually don’t increase “force potential” for APPROACH jumps in well-trained athletes. The peak forces are just far too low and far too slow. Now, most coaches know heavy squats won’t directly translate but some believe it increase "force potential". But the problem is that peak forces on heavy squats to parallel are normally even LOWER than the peak force of a standing jump. And approach jump peak forces are way beyond anything we could see in a parallel squat. So the idea that heavy parallel squats increases force potential must be hinged on the idea that we produce force over a longer period of time. I’d agree that a standing vertical jump may increase because a lot of heavy deep squats can train the athlete to get lower and produce force over a longer period of time (increase impulse by widening the curve). But in approach jumping we have strict time constraints on ground contact, which means we usually can’t increase impulse by widening the curve... we can only increase impulse by producing a higher peak force. So exercises that don’t involve high peak forces likely don’t have much transfer to approach jumping. 

This doesn’t mean half/deep squats are bad! There’s plenty of reasons to use them. But don’t expect your approach jumps to significantly increase by moving heavier weight in full range squats. Quarter squats would translate much better because of the high peak forces, but it’s STILL just potential. We typically see benefits when an athlete comes in weak and climbs to a 1.75x bodyweight quarter squat. Beyond 2x BW 1/4 squat safety might become an issue + low return on investment.

node.title: Do heavy squats really increase “force potential” in jumping?

We have to load in order to explode. But when athletes hear this they usually think it means they should do a bunch of slow/heavy eccentrics in order to improve “force absorption”. Truth is the lowering phase of a slow squat is the exact opposite of the lowering phase of a vertical jump when actually looking at the forces being produced! Over on the @theedgeu platform I just posted the full video teaching coaches the key points of ground reaction force in jumping and compared some exercises to give you an understanding of how we can mimic the braking forces of jumping in the weightroom. 

If you’re a coach, PT, fitness trainer or future trainer EdgeU is an unbelievable resource for you. You’ll get all my presentations, videos, research reviews and business advice along with @strong_by_science 🔥 nearly daily presentations. The amount of applicable content you receive for less than $1 per day should be a crime! Link in bio to join the EdgeU movement.
🎥 @thatcalvinmai 
🐰 @t.currie
📝 note- in this case study I only used 135 lbs on the back squat and rhythm quarters. Forces would be much higher with some real weight on the bar!

node.text:
Learn the 3 most important steps to successfully losing body fat while increasing athleticism! Hit the link in my bio for episode 31 of The PJF Podcast.

80-90% of people that lose weight will eventually regain that weight due to metabolic, behavioral, neuroendocrine, and autonomic responses designed to maintain body energy stores (fat) at a CNS- defined “ideal”. (Rosembaum & Leibel 2005) (M T McGuire et al. Obes Res. 1999).

It’s time to change up how you attack your fat loss! Get lean the right way if you want to stay lean long term!

Episode 31 is live on YouTube, apple podcasts, Spotify and Soundcloud.

Which one is your go-to pickup when help side defenders reach to get a steal? I’d say 1-4 are necessary to have in the bag. #5 is just a bonus! 

📝 Reminder we currently have our biggest sale of the year going on. 25% off all programs with code summergains25 🔋. Let’s build!

Let me know your athleticism/fitness goals below! The biggest sale of the year is LIVE. Use code summergains25 for 25% off ALL programs. 

-Vert Code Bodyweight- No equipment needed. 12 week program that can be done at home to significantly improve your bounce, speed, change of direction and overall athleticism.

Vert Code Elite- This program requires gym access and is designed for advanced, well trained athletes. This program is a full year! We focus on all aspects of athleticism with the number 1 priority being vertical jump.

Fat Don’t Fly- This is the best option to build insane relative strength/power. Get lean and shredded while building your athleticism. This is a full body training program + nutrition regimen. FDF also includes a detailed heart rate based conditioning program along with the full body strength protocol. This is the intersection of elite physique and elite athleticism development.

Speed Code- This is a 12 week program featuring world renowned speed coach @spellmanperformance. The priority of this program is speed, agility and quickness while also building vertical jump and overall athleticism. This program is being used by NFL, MLB, NBA and many other athletes of various different sports. Speed, agility and quickness is often the difference maker in sports. This program is the blueprint you need to take it to the next level. 

Ball Handling Program- 12 months worth of progressive ball handling drills along with agility, footwork and mobility. 

Hit the link in my bio and let’s get to work!

node.text:
Tag someone you treat like a parking cone on the court 👀. Here’s a quick clip of my nephew learning the importance of body angles. 

You might have seen the drill we used (cross/floor touch) many times before. But it’s really not about the drill, it’s about how the drill is used. 👉Skills before drills👈. By teaching the SKILL first and allowing him to feel it out and struggle a bit, it then gives the drill real context/meaning. Instead of mindlessly repping out the drill with no visualization and purpose, he was able to use the drill as a teaching tool that he immediately applied to the skill. 

Now everytime he goes back to that drill in the future he’ll “feel it” and visualize the actual game scenario. This is where drills become valuable instead of the typical mindless repetitions that don’t stick long term in the nervous system.

Day 13 #30Days30Drills

Go build.

Our biggest sale of the year is LIVE! 25% off ALL programs (monthly or lifetime options). Hit the link in my bio and use code summergains25 at checkout (all lower case).

Time to level up!! 🔋

How much time do you spend barefoot every day? 

Day 12 of #30Days30Drills we have some rough terrain walks. Our feet are designed to handle uneven surfaces/rough terrain. We often lose this ability because of our flat surfaces (court, sidewalks, etc) and our thick/stiff shoes. 

Most people can’t handle rocks just yet, but any natural surface that’s not perfectly level can be a good starting point. Even walking barefoot on grass is a good first step. Gradually work your way up to a rock mat or a bed of small rocks.

Let’s get our functional feet back! 

Go build.

Do you have this in the bag 🎒? Seems pretty easy… but 9/10 players I see actually struggle with a between change of direction without breaking stride and slowing down. This isn’t the footwork you’d use for most of your change of directions, but it does save valuable milliseconds when needed. 

Start by just doing between the legs at a slow jog pace WITHOUT breaking stride. Then gradually increase the pace until you can do it at full speed. 

To take your handle to a new stratosphere, check out our comprehensive ball handling program (link in bio). Starting today we are having our biggest sale of the year! 25% lifetime OR monthly with code summergains25

Let’s build. 

🎥 @draftexpress @sharife.cooper

What’s your age and what’s your athleticism goals? Let me know in the comments.

Day 11 of #30Days30Drills we have @dustystromer doing joint angle specific repeat jumps on the real jumper. Front foot is elevated for balance and our goal is to train specific knee angles in the back leg. These knee angles should closely mimic the angle of the plant foot of a 2 foot jump. 

This can also be performed with dumbbells and your front foot elevated on a small box. 

There’s some pre requisite stages we go through before doing drills like this!

node.text:
Comment your age and your athleticism/fitness goals! Day 10 of #30Days30Drills I’m doing a full body rotational row with our new @flexlinefitness 

This machine is awesome and I’d recommend it for any gym owners out there. Smooth air resistance that can be loaded heavier than you would ever need. You can increase or decrease resistance on the handle so you can get in place with no resistance and load it from there. Makes drop sets easier than ever. As a coach, I can carry around a handle and change the resistance from anywhere in the gym!

Day 9 of #30Days30Drills trying to make @therealmobamba into a gymnast with some beam work. 

This is a good warmup drill we use to build ankle/foot stability. Adding the hip hinge is great for building foot-glute connection. 

If you don’t have a beam, just walk an imaginary line. Heels up, strong/active foot, hinge from the hip! 

Let’s build.

node.text:
How tall are you and how close are you to dunking? Let me know below. 

Day 8 of #30Days30Drills we got @everybody_hatechriss working on his bounce in game scenarios. Chris isn’t just one of the best dunk contest dunkers in the world, he also has the ability to jump well in game situations. Drills like this should be performed by anyone looking to level up their in-game dunks. 

No amount of straight line approach dunk practice will translate. I’ve seen some great warmup dunkers that could never translate it to the game because they lacked variability in their dunk practice. 

Curved approaches, short approach distances, approaches off the dribble, etc… these are the reps that translate!

Tag someone that can’t guard you 1v1 👀. Here’s a cheat code for drawing fouls. At the lower levels you probably don’t need to worry about little tricks like this. But at the elite HS level + college and pro these small details go a long way! 

This video is from our TikTok (@pjfperformance). Follow our TikTok and YouTube for more basketball and training tips! We’ve been posting on those platforms every day for you guys. 

🎥 @thatcalvinmai
